{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778291065,"nonce":"+zQ9CKzK1TQQ5ysHdgt38+UBsPM=","title":"Sweep tau for LeakyRNNCell (vRNN) to find time-constant matching task scale","message":"User-proposed analysis from the 2×2×2 baseline matrix experiment (see `efc4d68` comment #5).\n\n## Motivation\n\nCurrent `tau=0.1` (α=0.1 leak per step) follows Yang 2019 / Sussillo 2015 / Michaels 2020 convention. The 2×2×2 matrix showed vRNN cells under-converge at 12k batches (final train loss ~10+ vs GRU 3.7) and produce nearly-identical velocity profiles across all 4 vRNN cells — cross-cell RMSE is nearly as low as within-cell RMSE. This pattern is consistent with the integration timescale being mismatched to the task scale. All vRNN conditions produce nearly the same behaviour, suggesting the network's internal dynamics are over-smoothed (tau too low → fast decay → insufficient memory) or under-driven relative to what the task requires.\n\n## Proposed sweep\n\nSweep `tau ∈ {0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.5}` on a baseline GRU/none-equivalent vRNN config (no smoothness, no jerk, 5 replicates, 12k batches). Pick the tau value that achieves comparable training-loss convergence to GRU (target: train loss \u003c 5.0 at 12k batches). Then re-run the 2×2×2 matrix with the selected tau.\n\n## Expected outcome\n\nA correctly-tuned tau should allow vRNN to converge to a similar loss level as GRU and produce meaningfully different replicates, making vRNN variance ratios comparable to GRU's.\n\n## Cross-refs\n\n- Part of the broader smoothness retrain investigation: `efc4d68`\n- Empirical cost-schedule sweep for comparison: `6ec6b19`","files":null}]}